In Java 8, the Function<T, R> interface is a functional interface used to represent a function that
accepts one input argument of type T and produces a result of type R.

ðŸ”¹ Function Interface - Overview
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Function<T, R> {
    R apply(T t);
}

T â€“ Input type
R â€“ Return type
Method: R apply(T t)
It also provides default methods like andThen() and compose() for function chaining.

âœ… Example 1: Simple Function â€“ Convert String to Integer length
import java.util.function.Function;
public class FunctionExample1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Function<String, Integer> stringLengthFunction = s -> s.length();
        System.out.println(stringLengthFunction.apply("Java")); // Output: 4
    }
}

âœ… Example 2: Square a number and convert to string
Function<Integer, Integer> square = n -> n * n;
Function<Integer, String> toString = n -> "Result: " + n;
Function<Integer, String> squareAndConvert = square.andThen(toString);
System.out.println(squareAndConvert.apply(5)); // Output: Result: 25

âœ… Example 3: Compose functions (first convert to double, then square)
Function<String, Integer> parse = s -> Integer.parseInt(s);
Function<Integer, Integer> square = x -> x * x;
Function<String, Integer> parseAndSquare = parse.andThen(square);
System.out.println(parseAndSquare.apply("6")); // Output: 36

ðŸ”¹ Real-World Use Case: Transform Employee to EmployeeDTO
class Employee {
    String name;
    int salary;
    Employee(String name, int salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }
}

class EmployeeDTO {
    String name;
    String info;
    EmployeeDTO(String name, String info) {
        this.name = name;
        this.info = info;
    }

    public String toString() {
        return name + " -> " + info;
    }
}

public class FunctionExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Function<Employee, EmployeeDTO> converter = e ->
            new EmployeeDTO(e.name, "Salary: " + e.salary);

        Employee emp = new Employee("John", 50000);
        System.out.println(converter.apply(emp));
    }
}

ðŸ”¹ Summary
| Feature           | Description                             |
| ----------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Functional method | `apply(T t)`                            |
| Purpose           | Transform data from one type to another |
| Use cases         | Mapping, transforming, chaining         |
| Common methods    | `apply()`, `andThen()`, `compose()`     |
